Roll of Honour of Clan McCrae's dead of <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a> at <a href="/wiki/Eilean_Donan" title="Eilean Donan">Eilean Donan</a> castle. <i>In Flanders Fields</i> features prominently.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>"<b>In Flanders Fields</b>" is one of the most famous <a href="/wiki/Media_of_World_War_I" title="Media of World War I">poems written during World War I</a> and has been called "the most popular poem" produced during that period.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It is written in the form of a French <a href="/wiki/Rondeau_(poetry)" title="Rondeau (poetry)">rondeau</a>. <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canadian</a> physician and Lieutenant Colonel <a href="/wiki/John_McCrae" title="John McCrae">John McCrae</a> wrote it on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1915-05-03"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="05-03"><a href="/wiki/May_3" title="May 3">May 3</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1915" title="1915">1915</a></span>, after he witnessed the death of his friend, Lieutenant Alexis Helmer, only 22 years old, the day before. The poem was first published on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="12-08"><a href="/wiki/December_8" title="December 8">December 8</a></span> of that year in the <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>-based magazine <i><a href="/wiki/Punch_(magazine)" title="Punch (magazine)">Punch</a></i>.</p>
