<li><a href="http://www.jonbrooks.ca" class="external text" title="http://www.jonbrooks.ca" rel="nofollow">In Flanders Fields</a>, new musical interpretation by award winning Canadian songwriter <a href="/wiki/Jon_Brooks" title="Jon Brooks">Jon Brooks</a>, released on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2007-05-03"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="05-03"><a href="/wiki/May_3" title="May 3">May 3</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2007" title="2007">2007</a></span></li>
<li><a href="http://www.english.emory.edu/LostPoets/" class="external text" title="http://www.english.emory.edu/LostPoets/" rel="nofollow">Lost Poets of the Great War</a>, a hypertext document on the poetry of World War I by <a href="/w/index.php?title=Harry_Rusche&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Harry Rusche (page does not exist)">Harry Rusche</a>, of the English Department, <a href="/wiki/Emory_University" title="Emory University">Emory University</a>, <a href="/wiki/Atlanta" title="Atlanta">Atlanta</a> <a href="/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)" title="Georgia (U.S. state)">Georgia</a>. It contains a bibliography of related materials.</li>
